From f81d736a2ecd7a034b62ad7737b1a313c11a5f97 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Sergey Fedorov <barracuda@macos-powerpc.org>
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 2026 19:04:05 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 07/10] feat(vendor): per-line dirty-tracking generation
 counter

The engine had NO way to tell a frontend which lines changed between two
frames: RenderBuffer is a flat, fully-rebuilt-every-frame cell/line list,
and Terminal::fillRenderBufferInternal() always recomposites the entire
visible page regardless of how little text actually changed. On a CPU
compositing backend (this port's default), a full-window recomposite +
reblit on every keystroke becomes perceptible once the page is large
enough -- symptom: typing feels laggy specifically in full screen (a much
bigger page than a normal window), back to normal on exiting it. Old
iTerm2 (same CPU/CoreGraphics era) does not have this problem because it
tracks dirty regions and only repaints what changed.

Adds a minimal, purely additive engine primitive to make that possible:

- LineSoA gains a `generation` counter (starts at 1), bumped by every
  function in LineSoA.h/SoAClusterWriter.h that mutates a line's content
  (initializeLineSoA, initializeBlankLineSoA, resizeLineSoA, clearRange,
  resetLine, copyColumns, moveColumns, appendCodepointToCluster,
  writeCellToSoA, fillWideCharContinuation, writeAsciiToSoA).
- BasicCellProxy<false> (the mutable CellProxy specialization used by
  Screen::writeText's whole per-character hot path) bumps it in its OWN
  destructor rather than in each of its ~15 individual setters
  (write/reset/setCharacter/setForegroundColor/.../setImageFragment):
  CellProxy holds a pointer into LineSoA, not a back-reference to the
  owning Line, so there is no single choke point below the proxy itself:
  every setter would need its own bump, and missing even one silently
  breaks dirty-tracking (a line that changed reads as unchanged -- stale
  content stuck on screen, a correctness bug, not just a missed
  optimization). A proxy existing at all means its caller intended to
  write through it (useCellAt's own name says so), so bumping
  unconditionally on destruction catches every real mutation by
  construction. The cost of the alternative failure mode -- an
  occasional false-positive "dirty" line that did not really change,
  e.g. a mutable proxy constructed but only read from -- is a lost
  redraw-skip opportunity, never incorrect output. ConstCellProxy
  (read-only, used by search/history-matching) does not bump: the
  destructor is `if constexpr` gated on the proxy being mutable.
- Line::generation() exposes the counter.
- RenderBuffer gains `lineGenerations` (std::vector<uint64_t>, indexed by
  screen row), populated by the new Terminal::captureLineGenerations(),
  which mirrors Grid::render()'s own row-range math exactly (scrollOffset
  + extraLines-for-smooth-scrolling + page size) so row N's generation
  corresponds to the exact same grid line Grid::render() just built
  RenderCells/RenderLines for.

This commit changes NO rendering behavor -- RenderBuffer.cells/lines/
cursor and every existing render path are untouched; lineGenerations is
new, optional-to-use data a frontend can ignore. The actual redraw-skip
logic (comparing this frame's lineGenerations against last frame's,
scoped invalidation via setNeedsDisplayInRect:/blit only the changed
rows) is frontend work, landing separately on the `frontend` branch --
this commit only makes it POSSIBLE.

A resize/scroll/reflow changes what row N even means (the row-index-to-
grid-line mapping shifts), which is why RenderBuffer.h's doc comment
requires a frontend to discard its last-frame snapshot whenever
pageSize()/scrollOffset() change rather than diffing blindly across
such a boundary -- a real correctness hazard the frontend, not this
commit, is responsible for handling.

